[2026-03-09T23:06:38Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01TfrcadTvmwxqHysXi2VA4e","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01W8BkU2etMYkmuoVHoancV2","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":624,"cache_read_input_tokens":14961,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":624,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Pph29ktHq7RQDisPYG79MQ","session_id":"97a77a59-727f-4b73-aabd-a95c79f375a5","uuid":"58502643-87c6-4ce8-9ef1-f33166fd70ac"}
[2026-03-09T23:06:38Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01W8BkU2etMYkmuoVHoancV2","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Workflows\n     2â†’\n     3â†’Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4â†’\n     5â†’## Workflow Locations\n     6â†’\n     7â†’Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8â†’\n     9â†’**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) â€” Run inside a Docker\n    10â†’container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11â†’standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12â†’\n    13â†’**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) â€” Runs on the host machine as the daemon\n    14â†’process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15â†’dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16â†’point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17â†’\n    18â†’The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    19â†’file is a parse error.\n    20â†’\n    21â†’## Concepts\n    22â†’\n    23â†’| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    24â†’|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    25â†’| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    26â†’| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    27â†’| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    28â†’| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    29â†’| done     | Built-in terminal step â€” successful completion                     |\n    30â†’| abort    | Built-in terminal step â€” failure with error reporting              |\n    31â†’\n    32â†’## Step Types\n    33â†’\n    34â†’Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    35â†’\n    36â†’**agent** (has `prompt`) â€” Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    37â†’to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    38â†’container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    39â†’\n    40â†’**script** (has `run`) â€” Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    41â†’any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    42â†’\n    43â†’**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) â€” Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    44â†’until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    45â†’\n    46â†’A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    47â†’parse error.\n    48â†’\n    49â†’## DSL Syntax\n    50â†’\n    51â†’```\n    52â†’workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    53â†’  step code {\n    54â†’    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    55â†’    container {\n    56â†’      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    57â†’      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    58â†’    }\n    59â†’    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    60â†’  }\n    61â†’\n    62â†’  step check {\n    63â†’    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    64â†’    results = [pass, fail]\n    65â†’  }\n    66â†’\n    67â†’  step review {\n    68â†’    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    69â†’    input = step.code.output\n    70â†’    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    71â†’  }\n    72â†’\n    73â†’  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n    74â†’  code:success -> check\n    75â†’  code:fail -> abort\n    76â†’  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n    77â†’\n    78â†’  check:pass -> review\n    79â†’  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n    80â†’\n    81â†’  review:approved -> done\n    82â†’  review:changes_requested -> code\n    83â†’}\n    84â†’```\n    85â†’\n    86â†’## Key Properties\n    87â†’\n    88â†’**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n    89â†’field makes it a script step.\n    90â†’\n    91â†’**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n    92â†’report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n    93â†’\n    94â†’**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n    95â†’existing ones by rewiring â€” without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n    96â†’Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n    97â†’\n    98â†’**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n    99â†’wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   100â†’\n   101â†’## Wire Output Mappings\n   102â†’\n   103â†’Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   104â†’them as environment variables into the target step:\n   105â†’\n   106â†’```\n   107â†’step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   108â†’```\n   109â†’\n   110â†’The general form:\n   111â†’\n   112â†’```\n   113â†’FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   114â†’```\n   115â†’\n   116â†’Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   117â†’starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   118â†’\n   119â†’| Expression | Meaning |\n   120â†’|---|---|\n   121â†’| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   122â†’| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   123â†’| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   124â†’| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   125â†’| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   126â†’\n   127â†’If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   128â†’structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   129â†’value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   130â†’\n   131â†’## Host Workflow Example\n   132â†’\n   133â†’```\n   134â†’# .cloche/host.cloche â€” runs on the host machine\n   135â†’workflow \"main\" {\n   136â†’  step prepare-prompt {\n   137â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   138â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   139â†’  }\n   140â†’\n   141â†’  step develop {\n   142â†’    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   143â†’    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n   144â†’    results       = [success, fail]\n   145â†’  }\n   146â†’\n   147â†’  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   148â†’  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   149â†’  develop:success        -> done\n   150â†’  develop:fail           -> done\n   151â†’}\n   152â†’```\n   153â†’\n   154â†’The `workflow_name` step reads the prompt from the previous step's output (or\n   155â†’`prompt_step` override), dispatches a container workflow run, and blocks until it\n   156â†’completes.\n   157â†’\n   158â†’## Execution Model\n   159â†’\n   160â†’**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   161â†’container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   162â†’wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   163â†’All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   164â†’\n   165â†’**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\n   166â†’steps run via `sh -c`, and workflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's\n   167â†’standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`,\n   168â†’etc.) are injected into each step.\n   169â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Pph29ktHq7RQDisPYG79MQ","session_id":"97a77a59-727f-4b73-aabd-a95c79f375a5","uuid":"0f72f3fd-4c72-4096-85a3-515330e81e71"}
